hy information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","246961"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122645","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-04-29","<p>The purpose of the Tampon Tax Fund is to allocate the funds generated from the VAT on sanitary products to projects that improve the lives of disadvantaged women and girls. The existing criteria for the Fund - with the focus on onwards grants to small and medium sized charities and direct support for vulnerable women and girls - maximise the reach and impact of the Tampon Tax Fund across the UK. Whether directly or through onwards grants, tampon tax fund is exclusively made available to projects that support vulnerable women and girls.</p>","Eastleigh","Mims Davies",,"2019-04-29T17:58:19.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122645/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122645/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122645/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-04-24","Sanitary Protection: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of restricting the Tampon Tax Fund to charities which specialise in women’s issues.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","247081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122646","Treasury","false","2019-05-01","<p>The Office of Financial Sanctions Implementation undertakes an annual review of frozen assets in the UK, requiring all persons or institutions that hold or control frozen assets in the UK to report to OFSI. Details of assets reported to OFSI in 2018 are not yet available and will be published in OFSI’s 2018-2019 Annual Review.</p><p> </p><p>There were no Burmese assets identified in the 2017 frozen asset review due to current designations coming into force from April 2018.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2019-05-01T15:06:15.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122646/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122646/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122646/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-04-24","Burma: Freezing of Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the value is of the assets frozen under EU sanctions on targeted Burmese military and security personnel.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","247082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122647","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-04-29","<p>Professor Dame Sue Hill, Chief Scientific Officer for NHS England, leads work to deliver the Government’s ambitions for diagnostics as part of the antimicrobial resistance (AMR) strategy. NHS England established the UK AMR Diagnostics Collaborative to support delivery of the United Kingdom’s diagnostics ambitions for AMR and development of the diagnostics elements of the new UK five-year national action plan on AMR, published in January this year.</p><p>The Department continues to work closely with the UK AMR Diagnostics Collaborative. NHS England advises that there are currently no plans to publish its data, but this may be revised in future.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-04-29T14:25:36.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122647/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122647/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122647/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-04-24","UK Antimicrobial Resistance Diagnostics Collaborative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if his Department will publish the data produced by Antimicrobial Resistance Diagnostics Collaborative.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","246987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122648","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-04-29","<p>The Department is working closely with delivery partners across Government to finalise governance arrangements and implementation plans for the commitments set out in the United Kingdom’s five-year national action plan for antimicrobial resistance. Agreed implementation arrangements will be shared as soon as practicable.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-04-29T14:33:11.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122648/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122648/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122648/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-04-24","Antimicrobials: Drug Resistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the answer of 18 March 2019 to Question 231971, if his Department will publish its plans for the implementation of Tackling antimicrobial resistance (2019-2024): The UK’s five-year national action plan; when this plan will be implemented; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","246988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122649","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-05-01","<p>​The UK remains committed to protecting vulnerable people, including the over one million forcibly displaced Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh. Up to 18 per cent of the Department for International Development's latest £70 million funding to the Rohingya crisis response in Bangladesh is devoted to the protection of rights for refugees, including prevention and monitoring of sexual exploitation and abuse.</p><p>The UK Preventing Sexual Violence in Conflict Initiative continues to work with the Government of Bangladesh, UN agencies and other stakeholders to strengthen justice and accountability for Rohingya survivors of sexual violence. UK funding includes support for family planning, clinical support to survivors of sexual violence and the creation of safe spaces for women.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2019-05-01T11:22:06.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122649/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122649/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122649/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-04-24","Bangladesh: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking with the Department for International Development to protect vulnerable people in refugee camps in Bangladesh from sexual violence.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","247083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122650","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-05-02","<p>The UK continues to press the Burmese authorities to implement the Annan Commission recommendations, and has discussed the issue with international partners in various fora. Most recently, I raised the issue with the Burmese National Security Adviser during his visit to London in March. We recognise that the Burmese Government has begun to respond to some of the recommendations but there is still much to be done. Through coordinated efforts at the United Nations, the UK has ensured a focus on Burma at the Security Council and Human Rights Council, including on the question of conditions in Rakhine. In January 2019 the Foreign Secretary discussed Burma with Foreign Minister Balakrishnan of Singapore; he has also met representatives of Non-Governmental Organisations working in Burma.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","247085","2019-05-02T14:55:44.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122650/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122650/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122650/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-04-24","Rakhine State Advisory Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to encourage the Burmese Government to adopt the recommendations made by the Advisory Commission on Rakhine State.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","247084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122651","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-05-02","<p>The UK continues to press the Burmese authorities to implement the Annan Commission recommendations, and has discussed the issue with international partners in various fora. Most recently, I raised the issue with the Burmese National Security Adviser during his visit to London in March. We recognise that the Burmese Government has begun to respond to some of the recommendations but there is still much to be done. Through coordinated efforts at the United Nations, the UK has ensured a focus on Burma at the Security Council and Human Rights Council, including on the question of conditions in Rakhine. In January 2019 the Foreign Secretary discussed Burma with Foreign Minister Balakrishnan of Singapore; he has also met representatives of Non-Governmental Organisations working in Burma.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","247084","2019-05-02T14:55:44.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122651/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122651/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122651/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-04-24","Rakhine State Advisory Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had on the recommendations of the Advisory Commission on Rakhine State with (a) UN officials, (b) NGOs and (c) counterparts from ASEAN nations.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","247085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122652","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-05-02","<p>The repatriation agreement between Burma and Bangladesh was signed on 23 November 2018. It has not been published, but the contents were widely reported in the media. We have previously raised our concerns in the House about the reported contents.</p><p> </p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2019-05-02T14:58:33.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122652/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122652/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122652/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-04-24","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether his Department has received a copy of the repatriation agreement between Burma and Bangladesh for Rohingyan refugees.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","247086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122653","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-05-02","<p>​The UK has been clear, as has the UN Security Council, that Burma must create the conditions in Rakhine to allow the Rohingya to return safely, voluntarily and with dignity. We agree with the UN High Commissioner for Refugees that these conditions do not yet exist. UN agencies also do not have the access they need to provide independent monitoring of any returns. The UK was deeply concerned when Bangladesh and Burma announced that the repatriation of refugees to Burma would begin in November 2018. We raised our concerns at the highest levels with both Governments, stressing that returns should not commence while conditions in northern Rakhine remain as they are. We welcome Bangladesh's commitment to the principle of &quot;voluntariness&quot; and were pleased that repatriations did not commence in November 2018. We will continue to make representations to the Governments of both Bangladesh and Burma not to commence returns until suitable conditions exist in northern Rakhine.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2019-05-02T15:02:51.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122653/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122653/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122653/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-04-24","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that Rohingyan refugees are not repatriated to Burma against their will.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","247087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122654","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-05-03","<p>The number of HMPPS band 3-5 prison officers in post, as at 31 December 2018, with less than three years’ experience in each prison can be found in the accompanying excel table.</p><p> </p><p>We commend our hard-working prison officers who do a vital job in protecting the public every day, often in challenging and difficult circumstances.</p><p> </p><p>We want prison officers to stay and progress their careers. We’ve improved induction processes to ease transition into the job, provide care and support for our staff and offer additional training. These measures are part of the work we are doing directly with Governors to address local issues and ensure experienced staff and new recruits remain in the service.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-05-03T13:54:19.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122654/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122654/answer","Copy of Copy of PQ 247088_final table.xlsx","Copy of Copy of PQ 247088_final table.xlsx","Table","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122654/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-04-24","Prison Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many officers in bands three to five in each prison operated by HMPPS have less than three years' experience.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","247088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122655","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-05-03","<p>The number of HMPPS band 3-5 prison officers in post, as at 31 December 2018, with three or more years’ experience in each prison can be found in the accompanying excel table.</p><p> </p><p>We commend our hard-working prison officers who do a vital job in protecting the public every day, often in challenging and difficult circumstances.</p><p> </p><p>We want prison officers to stay and progress their careers. We’ve improved induction processes to ease transition into the job, provide care and support for our staff and offer additional training. These measures are part of the work we are doing directly with Governors to address local issues and ensure experienced staff and new recruits remain in the service.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-05-03T13:56:29.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122655/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122655/answer","Copy of Copy of PQ 247089_final table.xlsx","Copy of Copy of PQ 247089_final table.xlsx","Table","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122655/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-04-24","Prison Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many officers in bands three to five in each prison operated by HMPPS have three or more years' experience.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","247089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122656","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-05-01","<p>Providers are not contractually obliged to supply data relating to the length of service of their employees. Responsibility for all staffing matters, including ensuring provision of sufficiently-trained and experienced staff to maintain safe and decent prisons, lies with the contractors. Regular recruitment and training of staff takes place across privately-managed prisons and we continue to monitor the performance of all providers closely.</p><p> </p><p>.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","247091","2019-05-01T13:26:07.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122656/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122656/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122656/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-04-24","Prison Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many officers in bands three to five or equivalent in each prison operated by private operators have less than three years' experience.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","247090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122657","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-05-01","<p>Providers are not contractually obliged to supply data relating to the length of service of their employees. Responsibility for all staffing matters, including ensuring provision of sufficiently-trained and experienced staff to maintain safe and decent prisons, lies with the contractors. Regular recruitment and training of staff takes place across privately-managed prisons and we continue to monitor the performance of all providers closely.</p><p> </p><p>.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","247090","2019-05-01T13:26:07.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122657/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122657/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122657/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-04-24","Prison Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many officers in bands three to five or equivalent in each prison operated by private operators have three or more years' experience.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","247091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122658","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-05-09","<p>The number of band 3-5 prison officers who left the prison service with less than a year’s service, by prison, can be found in the accompanying excel table.</p><p> </p><p>We want prison officers to stay and progress their careers. We’ve improved induction processes to ease transition into the job, provide care and support for our staff and offer additional training. These measures are part of the work we are doing directly with Governors to address local issues and ensure experienced staff and new recruits remain in the service.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-05-09T17:24:27.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122658/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122658/answer","PQ 247092 table.xlsx","PQ 247092 table.xlsx","PQ 247092 table","PQ 247092 table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122658/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-04-24","Prison Officers: Resignations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many officers in bands three to five in each prison left the prison service after less than a year in (a) 2010 and (b) 2018.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","247092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122659","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-05-01","<p>Her Majesty’s Prison and Probation Service (HMPPS) central accounting system does not separate specific costs in respect of new entry Prison Officers from other overall training costs. The information requested could only be obtained only at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2019-05-01T13:02:47.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122659/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122659/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122659/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-04-24","Prison Officers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much it costs the Ministry of Justice to train a new prison officer.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","247093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122660","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-05-01","<p>Information on where staff go after ending their employment with HMPPS is not held.</p><p> </p><p>We want prison officers to stay and progress their careers. We’ve improved induction processes to ease transition into the job, provide care and support for our staff and offer additional training. These measures are part of the work we are doing directly with Governors to address local issues and ensure experienced staff and new recruits remain in the service.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2019-05-01T18:56:27.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122660/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122660/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122660/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-04-24","Prison Officers: Resignations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prison officers in bands three to five left the prison service in 2018 to join (a) the police, (b) Border Force, (c) the military and (d) another profession.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","247094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122661","Department for Education","false","2019-05-01","<p>Information on private finance initiative (PFI) and private finance 2 data for current and in procurement projects published by HM Treasury can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-and-private-finance-2-projects-2017-summary-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-and-private-finance-2-projects-2017-summary-data</a>.</p><p>The PFI contracts for 6 schools in Leeds were signed between 1999 and 2008. Further data relating to PFI schools in Leeds is held by Leeds City Council.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-05-01T16:47:50.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122661/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122661/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122661/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122661/answer/previousversion/115438","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2019-04-24","Schools: Private Finance Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will publish the (a) names, (b) unitary charges, (c) costs and (d) project names of all PFI funded schools in Leeds.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","247031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122662","Department for Education","false","2019-05-01","<p>There is one private finance 2 (PF2) school in Sandwell (the Phoenix Collegiate) in the Priority School Building Programme privately financed Midlands batch.</p><p> </p><p>Information on private finance initiative (PFI) and PF2 data for current and in procurement projects published by HM Treasury can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-and-private-finance-2-projects-2017-summary-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-and-private-finance-2-projects-2017-summary-data</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Further data relating to PFI schools in Sandwell is held by Sandwell Metropolitan Borough Council.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-05-01T16:51:45.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122662/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122662/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122662/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122662/answer/previousversion/115439","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2019-04-24","Schools: Private Finance Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will publish the (a) names, (b) unitary charges (c) costs and (d) project names of all PFI funded schools in Sandwell.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","247032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122663","Department for Education","false","2019-05-01","<p>Information on private finance initiative (PFI) and private finance 2 data for current and in procurement projects published by HM Treasury can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-and-private-finance-2-projects-2017-summary-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-and-private-finance-2-projects-2017-summary-data</a>.</p><p>Three schools’ PFI contracts in Tameside were signed between 2002 and 2010. Further data relating to PFI schools in Tameside is held by Tameside Metropolitan Borough Council.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-05-01T16:42:22.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122663/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122663/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122663/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122663/answer/previousversion/115437","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2019-04-24","Schools: Private Finance Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will publish the (a) names, (b) unitary charges (c) costs and (d) project names of all PFI funded schools in Tameside.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","247033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122664","Department for Education","false","2019-05-01","<p>Information on private finance initiative (PFI) and private finance 2 (PF2) data for current and in procurement projects published by HM Treasury can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-and-private-finance-2-projects-2017-summary-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-and-private-finance-2-projects-2017-summary-data</a>.</p><p>One school PFI contract in Luton was signed in 2009. Additionally, there is one PF2 school in Luton (Stopsley High School) within the Priority School Building Programme private finance Hertfordshire, Luton and Reading batch.</p><p>Further data relating to PFI schools in Luton is held by Luton Borough Council.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-05-01T16:52:58.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122664/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122664/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122664/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122664/answer/previousversion/115440","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2019-04-24","Stopsley School: Private Finance Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which PFI progamme includes the Sopsley High School in Luton; and who the shareholders of the Special-Purpose Vehicle for that school are.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","247034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122665","Department for Education","false","2019-05-01","<p>Information on private finance initiative (PFI) and private finance 2 data for current and in procurement projects published by HM Treasury can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-and-private-finance-2-projects-2017-summary-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-and-private-finance-2-projects-2017-summary-data</a>.</p><p>The PFI contracts for 2 schools in Newham were signed in 2001 and 2003. Further data relating to PFI schools in Newham is held by the London Borough of Newham.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-05-01T16:51:37.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122665/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122665/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122665/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122665/answer/previousversion/115435","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2019-04-24","Schools: Private Finance Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which PFI programme includes the Joining Schools Project in Newham; and who the shareholders of the Special-Purpose Vehicle for that school are.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","247035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122666","Department for Transport","false","2019-04-29","<p>The Office of Rail and Road (ORR) regulate Network Rail, holding it to account for delivering high levels of performance and service, as well as good value for money – for passengers, the freight industry and taxpayers. The ORR are accountable to Parliament and the public.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State sets the high-level strategy for Network Rail, though Network Rail retains a high degree of autonomy in how it meets the aims of that strategy. The Secretary of State of Transport is accountable to Parliament for the activities and performance of Network Rail.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-04-29T13:41:16.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122666/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122666/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122666/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-04-24","East Coast Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 23 April 2019 to Question 243447 on the East Coast Railway Line, through which Government Department Members of Parliament can hold Network Rail accountable for its performance.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","247052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122667","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-05-01","<p>We welcome this positive declaration of the reinstatement of citizenship for 551 Bahrain citizens on 21 April.</p><p> </p><p>We regularly raise our concerns about the issue of revocation of nationalities where it leaves a person stateless at a senior level with the Government of Bahrain.</p><p>​</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2019-05-01T16:10:51.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122667/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122667/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122667/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-04-24","Bahrain: Nationality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether his Department made any representations to the Bahraini authorities calling for the reinstatement of citizenship for Bahraini citizens previously convicted of crimes related to political dissent, before the Kingdom of Bahrain reinstated the citizenship of 551 people on 21 April 2019.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","246910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122668","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-05-03","<p>Government recognises the important role that the creative industries play in driving local growth and creating new opportunities in places across the UK.</p><p>To support the UK’s world-leading cultural and creative businesses, the government and industry invested £150 million in the Creative Industries Sector Deal.</p><p>The Deal announced several proposals including a £20 million ‘Cultural Development Fund’ (CDF) for cities and towns in England to bid for creative and cultural investment. As part of the competitive grant application process, the following towns and cities were successful in their CDF application: Worcester, Wakefield, Thames Estuary, Plymouth and Grimsby. In addition, a £39m ‘Creative Industries Cluster Programme’ funding for nine R&amp;D partnerships has been set up across the UK.</p><p>The Department for Digital, Culture, Media &amp; Sport also funds Arms Length Bodies such as Arts Council England which invest in arts and culture on a regional basis.</p><p>According to Arts Council England, National Portfolio Organisations in Cornwall - many of which are defined as Creative Industries - will receive up to £10 million in funding between 2018-22. In addition, a further £5.96 million has been invested in Music Education Hubs and Grants for the Arts between 2013 and 2019</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2019-05-03T12:16:57.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122668/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122668/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122668/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-04-24","Culture: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to ensure that areas such as North Cornwall get their fair share of Creative Industries funding after a previous unsuccessful bid.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","247135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122669","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-05-03","<p>The Department has made no such estimate.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-05-03T13:18:10.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122669/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122669/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122669/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-04-24","Orkambi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate his Department has made of the value of packs of Orkambi that have been disposed of while negotiations between NHS England and Vertex Pharmaceuticals are ongoing.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","247136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122670","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-05-02","<p>The Department has made no such assessment.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2019-05-02T13:40:28.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122670/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122670/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122670/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-04-24","X-rays","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment his Department has made of whether hospitals frequently need to rely on the family members of patients to assist in x-ray procedures.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","247137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122671","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-05-02","<p>We are committed to protecting the IP of our world leading Creative Industries, which is why are continuing to support The &quot;Get It Right&quot; campaign with £2M investment over 3 years. This campaign is part of The Government's Sector Deal which helps educate consumers on the dangers of copyright infringement and directs them towards legitimate sources of creative content online. The HM Ambassador in Riyadh has raised this matter on a number of occasions with Ministers in the Saudi Arabian Government.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2019-05-02T12:41:51.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122671/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122671/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122671/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-04-24","Arts: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on grassroots funding for the arts of the widespread theft of the UK creative industries intellectual property rights by the pirate network beoutQ.","false","Biography information for Giles Watling","Clacton","Giles Watling","247159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122672","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-05-01","<p>The Review of Build Out Rates chaired by the Rt Hon Sir Oliver Letwin MP reported on 29 October 2018. It found no evidence that speculative land banking is part of the business model for major house-builders, or that it explains slow build-out rates. The review concluded that greater differentiation in types and tenures of new homes would increase market absorption and stimulate an increase in build-out rates. This Government has put in place extensive incentives and assistance to encourage house-building, especially on brownfield land, to support the housing policies in our revised National Planning Policy Framework.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2019-05-01T15:46:05.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122672/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122672/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122672/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-04-24","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, if he will make an assessment of the quantity of land suitable for housing being left undeveloped due to land banking by private developers.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","247002"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122673","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-04-29","<table><tbody><tr><td><p>The Government conducted a consultation on our proposals for an Independent Public Advocate (IPA) which concluded on the 3rd December 2018. We are considering the response to those proposals and will be publishing our plans for establishing the IPA in due course.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2019-04-29T10:04:54.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122673/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122673/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122673/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-04-24","Disasters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what progress has been made on implementing the commitment in the Queen's Speech 2017 to introduce an independent public advocate who will act for bereaved families after a public disaster and support them at public inquests; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","246937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122674","Home Office","false","2019-04-29","<p>Rt Rev James Jones KBE's 2017 report recommended that consideration be given to the Public Authority (Accountability) Bill &quot;once the Law Commission's work on Misconduct in Public Office is complete, and government has agreed the detail of the reform the Commission sets out&quot;.</p><p>The Law Commission's work is currently on-going. Once the review of Misconduct in Public Office is complete, Government will consider and respond to the Law Commission's conclusions. The Government will also provide a full response to the 2017 report in due course, following the conclusion of the ongoing criminal proceedings.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2019-04-29T13:20:12.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122674/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122674/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122674/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-04-24","Public Authority (Accountability) Bill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if he will take steps to introduce the provisions set out in the Public Authority (Accountability) Bill recommended by the Rt RevJames Jones KBE in his report, The patronising disposition of unaccountable power: a  report to ensure the pain and suffering of the Hillsborough families is not repeated, published on 1 November 2017, HC 511; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","246938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122675","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-05-03","<p>The Department fully understands that maintaining access to Riluzole (Rilutek) for the management of motor neurone disease is vitally important to many people in this country. We are aware that there was a supply issue with Riluzole earlier this year which resulted in limited supplies during February and early March, and worked closely with suppliers to manage this.</p><p>Supplies of Riluzole 50 milligram tablets are currently available in volumes that are sufficient to meet normal United Kingdom demand. The Department continues to work very closely with all the manufacturers of Riluzole 50 milligram tablets and can confirm that the supply situation continues to improve with further deliveries expected over the coming months. All patients who require Riluzole 50 milligram tablets should be able to obtain a supply from their pharmacy.</p><p>We continue to work closely with industry and partners in the health system to help prevent shortages and to ensure that the risks to patients are minimised when supply issues do arise.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-05-03T13:19:20.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122675/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122675/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122675/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-04-24","Riluzole","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to increase the supply of Rilutek for people with motor neurone disease, and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","246969"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122676","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-05-02","<p>The information is not available.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince",,"2019-05-02T16:23:51.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122676/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122676/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122676/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-04-24","Department for Work and Pensions: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many complaints have been submitted by Ministers in the Department on behalf of their constituents for each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","247098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122677","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-04-29","<p>To provide a reply would require the Department to link together several complex datasets and quality assure the results. Although theoretically possible, it is estimated that this would take in excess of 4 working days therefore as the information requested is not readily available, to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2019-04-29T11:55:18.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122677/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122677/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122677/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-04-24","Work Capability Assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants have died within (a) six months and (b) 12 months after being assessed as fit for work.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","246936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122678","Department for Education","false","2019-05-02","<p>We will publish both the number of schools that were made an offer of support, the number that accepted the support, and the methodology used to determine eligibility for the Opportunity North East’s ONE Vision Schools programme in due course.</p><p>The ONE Vision programme aims to improve outcomes for young people at key stages 4 and 5 in 30 secondary phase schools. We selected Ofsted Requires Improvement (RI) as the single indicator to identify the long list of secondary phase schools in scope to become a ONE Vision school and, by exception<strong>, </strong>Ofsted Inadequate schools. We then shortlisted schools using a comprehensive review of their performance data, pupil demographics, Ofsted history and intelligence from local authorities and trusts on which schools were priorities for support. We made an initial offer of support to 32 schools, of which 30 accepted.</p><p>The support that each ONE Vision school receives will be bespoke to their individual circumstances. It will be determined by an analysis of need comprising an External Review of Governance, undertaken by a National Leader of Governance; a Financial Health Check, undertaken by a School Resource Management Adviser; and a School Development Review, undertaken by a National Leader of Education or other high performing school leader. This analysis will identify the schools’ main priorities for improvement.</p><p>The following table shows the number of pupils in 2017/18 (a) attending all state-funded mainstream schools in the North East who are in the region’s lowest quintile of Attainment 8 scores, and (b) attending ONE Vision Schools who are within the region’s lowest quintile of Attainment 8 scores.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Number of pupils in North East in lowest quintile[1] of Attainment 8 scores (state-funded mainstream schools[2])</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of pupils in North East in One Vision schools in lowest quintile<sup>1</sup> of Attainment 8 scores (state-funded mainstream schools<sup>2</sup>)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>4,836</p></td><td><p>1,169</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The following table shows the number of pupils in 2017/18 (a) attending all state-funded schools in the North East who are within the region’s lowest quintile of capped GCSE point scores, based on their best eight entries, and (b) attending ONE Vision Schools who are within the region’s lowest quintile of capped GCSE point scores, based on their best eight entries.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Number of pupils in North East in lowest quintile<sup>1</sup> of best eight entries scores (all state-funded schools)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of pupils in North East in One Vision schools in lowest quintile<sup>1</sup> of best eight entries scores (all state-funded schools)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>4,879</p></td><td><p>1,135</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>It is a goal of the ONE Vision programme to build capacity in these 30 schools so that they are able to support other schools in the future. To ensure that the ONE Vision activity does not adversely affect schools that are not participating in the programme, we will continue to speak with local authorities and trusts as part of our monitoring activities to understand what impact ONE Vision is having on the wider community. We will also continue to monitor the performance of all schools across the region.</p><p> </p><p>[1] Quintiles are based on pupil ranking rather than school ranking. As more than one pupil can have the same attainment score, more than 20 percent of pupils can have scores in the lowest 20 percent.</p><p>[2] Region figures cover achievements in state-funded schools only. They do not include pupils recently arrived from overseas.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","247054 ; 247055 ; 247056 ; 247057 ; 247058","2019-05-02T12:27:08.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122678/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122678/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122678/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-04-24","Schools: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will publish the number of schools (a) offered support under Opportunity North East’s ONE Vision programme and (b) that have indicated they will accept that support.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","247053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122679","Department for Education","false","2019-05-02","<p>We will publish both the number of schools that were made an offer of support, the number that accepted the support, and the methodology used to determine eligibility for the Opportunity North East’s ONE Vision Schools programme in due course.</p><p>The ONE Vision programme aims to improve outcomes for young people at key stages 4 and 5 in 30 secondary phase schools. We selected Ofsted Requires Improvement (RI) as the single indicator to identify the long list of secondary phase schools in scope to become a ONE Vision school and, by exception<strong>, </strong>Ofsted Inadequate schools. We then shortlisted schools using a comprehensive review of their performance data, pupil demographics, Ofsted history and intelligence from local authorities and trusts on which schools were priorities for support. We made an initial offer of support to 32 schools, of which 30 accepted.</p><p>The support that each ONE Vision school receives will be bespoke to their individual circumstances. It will be determined by an analysis of need comprising an External Review of Governance, undertaken by a National Leader of Governance; a Financial Health Check, undertaken by a School Resource Management Adviser; and a School Development Review, undertaken by a National Leader of Education or other high performing school leader. This analysis will identify the schools’ main priorities for improvement.</p><p>The following table shows the number of pupils in 2017/18 (a) attending all state-funded mainstream schools in the North East who are in the region’s lowest quintile of Attainment 8 scores, and (b) attending ONE Vision Schools who are within the region’s lowest quintile of Attainment 8 scores.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Number of pupils in North East in lowest quintile[1] of Attainment 8 scores (state-funded mainstream schools[2])</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of pupils in North East in One Vision schools in lowest quintile<sup>1</sup> of Attainment 8 scores (state-funded mainstream schools<sup>2</sup>)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>4,836</p></td><td><p>1,169</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The following table shows the number of pupils in 2017/18 (a) attending all state-funded schools in the North East who are within the region’s lowest quintile of capped GCSE point scores, based on their best eight entries, and (b) attending ONE Vision Schools who are within the region’s lowest quintile of capped GCSE point scores, based on their best eight entries.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Number of pupils in North East in lowest quintile<sup>1</sup> of best eight entries scores (all state-funded schools)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of pupils in North East in One Vision schools in lowest quintile<sup>1</sup> of best eight entries scores (all state-funded schools)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>4,879</p></td><td><p>1,135</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>It is a goal of the ONE Vision programme to build capacity in these 30 schools so that they are able to support other schools in the future. To ensure that the ONE Vision activity does not adversely affect schools that are not participating in the programme, we will continue to speak with local authorities and trusts as part of our monitoring activities to understand what impact ONE Vision is having on the wider community. We will also continue to monitor the performance of all schools across the region.</p><p> </p><p>[1] Quintiles are based on pupil ranking rather than school ranking. As more than one pupil can have the same attainment score, more than 20 percent of pupils can have scores in the lowest 20 percent.</p><p>[2] Region figures cover achievements in state-funded schools only. They do not include pupils recently arrived from overseas.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","247053 ; 247055 ; 247056 ; 247057 ; 247058","2019-05-02T12:27